## Introduction (continued): Why Bloom Beat LTCM

### Bloom's Three Advantages Over LTCM

- **LTCM's fatal flaw**: Mathematical models based on historical data told them their holdings would never fall so much. Markets obliterated previously established relationships among asset prices.
- **Bloom's advantage #1 - Time**: Decades of compounding (67 years vs. LTCM's 4 years barely surviving)

> "Compound interest is the eighth wonder of the world. He who understands it, earns it. He who doesn't, pays it." — **Albert Einstein** (apocryphal)

- **Bloom's advantage #2 - Patience**: Slow wealth accumulation, not get-rich-quick. Turned secretary's salary into millions through magic of compounding over 67 years.
- **Key lesson**: Worst thing you can do is cut compounding short with "dumb stuff": leverage, chasing star money managers, overestimating risk tolerance, watching financial cable shows.

### Bloom's Frugality

- **Third advantage**: Frugality, but not deprivation
- Dressed well, sported fur coat occasionally, traveled frequently with husband
- 9/11 example: 84-year-old walked across Brooklyn Bridge and took bus home during snowstorm
- Friend **Paul Hyams** saw her climbing out of subway, asked "Why, where should I be?"
- **Answer**: Had she lived more lavishly, wouldn't have left such large estate
- **Purpose of saving**: To spend later — in Bloom's case, on charity, not herself

### Core Investment Principle

> "Investing, distilled to its essence, is the conveyance of assets from your present self to your future self."

- Financial highway between present and future self is "strewn with black ice and massive potholes"
- Portfolio's lifetime route winds through 2-3 versions of "treacherous mountain passes with no guardrails" — **bear markets** during financial panics
- **Manifestly**: The more slowly you drive, the more likely assets arrive safely at destination
- Bloom drove slowly; LTCM's principals put pedal to metal

> "To make money they didn't have and didn't need, they risked what they did have and did need." — **Warren Buffett**

### Why Bloom Succeeded and LTCM Failed

- Bloom's strategy **survived**; LTCM's strategy **risked out**
- Finance professionals often deem light-on-stocks portfolios "suboptimal"
- **Better framing**: "Suboptimal" strategy that survives fear/panic is preferable to optimal one that takes unnecessary risk

### Investing Is Half Math, Half Shakespeare

- **Robert Kaplan** (historian): "Half of everything is geography; the other half is Shakespeare"
- **Investing parallel**: Half math (**Mr. Spock**), half Shakespeare (human irrationality)
- Math side: dry, essential, mathematical part of finance
- Shakespeare side: fear suffusing bear markets, empathy, tendency to imitate, channel fear/greed of others, privilege narratives over data
- **Hamlet, Lear, Macbeth**: The all-too-human irrationality in human endeavor and cruel mistress of history
- Often math and Shakespeare are diametrically opposed — if you don't master Shakespeare, world won't help you
- Shakespeare is NOT art/poetry but rather irrationality expressed in human endeavor

**Solution**: Master the **Four Pillars of Investing**

