## PILLAR ONE: INVESTMENT THEORY

### The Central Principle: Risk and Return

> "If you learn nothing else from this book, it should be this: risk and return go hand in hand."

- Cannot expect high returns without experiencing occasional bone-crushing losses
- Internet bubble of late 1990s: stock that increases 900% one year can just as easily fall 90% the next
- **No way** of avoiding risks that come with common stocks
- **No market timing fairy** who can reliably tell you when to exit stock market
- Market Cassandras abound at every moment; in every crash, one or two will call it perfectly by chance
- Subsequent predictions of these "geniuses" fare worse than coin flip
- **Example**: From market peak late 2007 to low early March 2009, S&P 500 fell 55.2% (including dividends). By end of 2022, gained 644% from that low point.

### The Price of Stock Market Returns

> "I do not think it is the business, far less the duty, of an institutional or any other serious investor to be constantly considering whether he should cut and run on a falling market, or to feel himself open to blame if shares depreciate on his hands. I would go much further than that. I should say that it is from time to time the duty of the serious investor to accept the depreciation of his holdings with equanimity and without reproaching himself." — **John Maynard Keynes**

### Equanimity: The Key Word

- **Equanimity**: ability to bear losses calmly and as ordinary matter of course
- Most potent elixir of financial equanimity: **large pile of safe assets**
- For US investor: dull, low-yielding **Treasury securities** allow you to hold on when things look darkest
- Treasury securities are highest-returning asset in portfolio (secret ignored by LTCM's principals)

### Life-Cycle Investing Evolution

- Author's thoughts on life-cycle investing evolved over two decades
- Key determinants of stock risk: **investor's age** and her **"burn rate"** (how much of portfolio gets spent each year)
- Discussion of how to vary asset allocation throughout life cycle moved to end of "theory" section in Chapter 6

---

## PILLAR TWO: INVESTMENT HISTORY

### Long-Term vs. Short-Term Market Behavior

- Over decades/centuries: capital markets neat and tidy as English aristocrat's rose garden
- Stocks return more than bonds; bonds return more than cash; all approximately predictable
- Over periods as long as several years: markets can go off rails
- **Late 1990s**: companies needed only eyeballs and clicks (forget earnings/dividends) to command ionospheric prices
- **Early 1930s**: shares of some companies sold for less than value of their **cash on hand**

### The 1999 Dinner Party Test

- If transported to 1999 dinner party, topic A: stupendous amounts of money made by tech investors
- Easiest way to pick who got rich: administer brief quiz on **1929 crash**
- How was **Goldman Sachs** involved? Who was **Samuel Insull**?

### Finance Is a Social Science, Not Hard Science

- **Key difference**: Bridge, electrical circuit, aircraft always respond same way to given circumstances
- **Financial markets do not** — hard fact that brought LTCM's principals and clients to grief
- Physician, physicist, chemist unaware of their discipline's history doesn't suffer greatly
- **Investor unaware of financial history is irretrievably handicapped**

### Two Historical Concepts Investors Must Know

1. **Long-term returns and short-term volatilities** of various asset classes
2. How **Mr. Market** (**Benjamin Graham's** term) suffers from severe **bipolar disorder** — periodically swinging between extremes of euphoria and depression

---

## PILLAR THREE: INVESTMENT PSYCHOLOGY

### The Stone Age Brain Problem

- Late-Pleistocene ancestors lived in world where hair-trigger reactions meant life or death
- Over hundreds of thousands of years, species evolved lightning-fast behaviors exquisitely adapted to that environment
- **300 generations** after end of last ice age, we live in financial world whose risk horizon measured in **decades, not seconds**
- Investor's greatest enemy: **Stone Age face staring back in mirror**

### The Skunk Analogy

- **Skunk strategy**: Over millions of years, evolved effective strategy for dealing with large predators with sharp teeth: turn 180 degrees and spray
- Response doesn't work well in semi-urban environment where biggest threat is "hunk of metal moving at 60 miles per hour"
- **Humans**: investing equivalents of modern skunk
- **Behavioral finance**: received a lot of attention (perhaps too much) but still can teach us

### Common Mistakes of Unsuccessful Investors

- **Grossly overconfident**: about ability to time market, pick stocks/successful asset managers, and even worse, about **risk tolerance**
- **Overpay** for certain classes of stocks
- **Trade too much**, at great cost
- **Seek out financial choices** with low probabilities of high payoffs but low long-term returns (IPOs, lottery tickets)

> "One of the quickest ways to the poorhouse is to make finding the next Amazon.com your primary investing goal."

**Learning to deal with these foibles pays generous stream of dividends**

---

## PILLAR FOUR: THE BUSINESS OF INVESTMENT

### The Financial Services Industry as Battlefield

> "The prudent traveler stays away from war zones."

- Can treat entire financial services industry as battlefield
- Any stockbroker/full-service brokerage firm, any newsletter, any advisor who purchases individual securities, any hedge fund
- **Comparison**: Average stockbroker services clients same way **Baby Face Nelson** serviced banks

### Industry Problems

- **Shocking ignorance** of fundamentals of investment theory among many financial advisors/brokers
- **Reason**: Neither industry nor government imposes educational requirements on brokers/financial advisors, or on managers of hedge/pension/mutual funds
- Industry observes "moral code that would give tobacco industry a run for its money"
- **Zero-sum battle** with this behemoth

### The Good News: Low-Cost Index Funds

- When book's first edition published two decades ago: only one safe place was **Vanguard Group's family of low-cost mutual funds**
- Other major investment firms, having had lunches eaten by Vanguard, decided to join it
- Began offering wide range of inexpensive mutual funds and ETFs, even on their own platforms
- Vanguard became victim of its own success, poorly handled flood of new customers
- **Remains viable choice, but certainly now not the only one**

