## Chapter 18: Nuts and Bolts

### The Evolution of Index Investing

**First edition (two decades ago):** Simple recommendations
- Set up Vanguard account, buy index funds
- Only serious alternative: **Dimensional Fund Advisors (DFA)** — filled deep-value corners better than Vanguard behemoth
- DFA required expensive affiliated advisor services
- Lucky few had access through employer DC plans

**Current situation:** DFA products now available to public as **exchange-traded funds (ETFs)**
- Plenty of competition in factor tilt (small/value) department
- Biggest beneficiary of "Bogle revolution": **defined-contribution plans**

## Most Improved Player Award: The 401(k)

### The Shift from DB to DC Plans

- Past decades: companies gradually closed traditional **defined-benefit pensions** (provided pensions to retired workers)
- Replaced with **defined-contribution schemes**, most commonly **401(k)s**

**Impact:** Offloaded shortfall risk from employers to employees
- Good for employers, bad for workers
- Saving, investing, spending for retirement requires ability, investment knowledge, self-discipline
- Strains credulity to expect average worker to execute well
- Analogy: "Imagine boarding airliner. Instead of heading to seat, flight attendant tells you pilots decided to stay home because of risk/stress. Turn left at door, you fly the plane."

### Why Employers Love DC Plans

- Inexpensive to fund and administer
- Until recently, effectively shielded from liability
- Employers paid scant attention to fund expenses
- Before 2005: typical plan had overt costs **at least 2% per year** before hidden administrative fees

### The Dark Ages of 401(k)s (1990s-2000s)

**1990s stock fund offerings:**
- Heavily weighted with large-cap glamour companies of the period
- Many participants selected highest-returning funds on plan list (most often high-octane tech funds)
- Did not turn out well

**Bottom of pile:** Teachers' 403(b) and government employees' 457 accounts
- Larded with funds featuring eye-watering fees, often from insurance companies

### The Improvement Era

**Past few decades transformation:**
- Average DC plan improved dramatically
- Word of Vanguard advantage spread among general public, employees, employers
- Most plans now offer decent array of low-cost passive vehicles

**Key contributors:**

1. **Behavioral economists** (e.g., **Richard Thaler**) — made inexpensive, easy-to-deploy target-date funds default choice in many schemes

2. **Research firms** (e.g., **BrightScope**) — applied sunlight disinfectant to exploitative Byzantine fee structures

3. **Tort attorney Jerome Schlichter** — did well by doing good, continues dozens of high-profile cases against large companies failing fiduciary responsibilities
- Bad old days: "Nobody's bonus depended on how the 401(k) plan was managed"
- Few attorneys have honor of past participle named after them
- **"Schlichterized"** — fearsome prospect for corporate legal departments

**Result:** 401(k) plan should feature decent selection of low-cost index and target-date funds

**Remaining problems:** Still many old plans with miserable, high-cost actively managed mutual funds
- If see insurance company names in list: HR director may be enjoying plan administrator's skybox seats
- Protest if possible; if not, take maximum employer match advantage, invest within income/living expense limits
- Save beyond that in personal IRA at low-cost provider
- **Upon employment termination:** Roll assets into personal IRA

## Your Personal Accounts

### The Vanguard Effect

**Historical dominance:** Until recently, **John Bogle's Vanguard Group** stood head and shoulders above everyone in delivering best funds at lowest cost

**The game changer:** What **Bloomberg analyst Eric Balchunas** labeled **"The Vanguard Effect"**
- Existential threat to other large investment companies (Fidelity, Schwab, old wire houses)
- Forced rest of industry to compete with Vanguard on price

### Current Competitive Landscape

**Competition intensification:**
- Schwab and Fidelity have lineup of dirt-cheap, open-end index funds
- Some Fidelity funds have **zero expense ratio**
- Investors can now assemble rock-bottom-cost ETF portfolios at many brokerages, including Vanguard's (free of commissions and fees)

**Quality gap largely gone:**
- As Bogle admirer, pains author to admit: **Vanguard customer support has deteriorated**
- Not infrequent clerical errors, extended phone hold times
- Contrast: generally fast, knowledgeable, accurate support at other firms

**How long will free ride last at Fidelity/Schwab?**
- Anyone's guess — enjoy while it does

## To ETF or Not to ETF

### ETF Growth Explosion

**1993:** State Street Global Advisors listed first ETF
- Ticker: **SPY**
- Better known as **SPDR** (Standard & Poor's Depository Receipts)

**Growth trajectory:**
- 1993: 1 ETF
- Decade later (2003): 276 ETFs
- 2021: **8,552 ETFs**
- Until 2008: all ETFs passively managed
- Today: **98% still passively managed**

### Choice Paralysis

**Small investor problem:** Major-league choice paralysis
- Multiple providers offer ETFs in every conceivable asset class
- **DC plan participants largely protected** — most large/midsize company plans limit picks to relatively few plain-vanilla open-end vehicles, don't offer ETFs

### ETFs vs Open-End Funds: Performance

**For most encompassing asset classes** (US total stock market, S&P 500, MSCI EAFE, foreign developed stocks):
- ETFs and open-end mutual funds from major providers have **low expense ratios**
- Provide **nearly identical returns** in most cases

**Holdings comparison example:**
- **Schwab International Index Fund** (open-end): owns only **855 names**
- **ETF version:** owns **1,527 names**
- **Vanguard offerings:** own **7,881 names**
- Even this large difference has little long-term return effect (missing names in Schwab funds = small market cap firms)

### Housing Your Accounts: Rules of the Road

**Big Three: Vanguard, Schwab, Fidelity**

1. **Open-end fund purchases:** Limit to custodian's own funds
   - Example: If assets at Fidelity, use only Fidelity's open-end index funds

2. **ETF trading:**
   - Can trade ETFs from any company **commission-free** at all three brokerages (online)
   - Trades through live broker likely incur commission
   - **Always place ETF trades as limit order**
   - **Avoid first and last 30 minutes** of trading day (pricing and spreads can be erratic)
   - Pay attention to **price spreads** (listed in chapter tables, particularly for smaller funds)
   - Current spread data easily available from firms' websites (Fidelity especially easy to navigate)

3. **Treasuries:**
   - Can be purchased at auction **commission-free** at all three companies
   - **Secondary market trading** (after auction, before maturity): confirm commission details with brokerage
   - Especially important at Schwab (sweep vehicle money market yields well below market levels)

4. **Banking:**
   - Fidelity and Schwab offer online banking
   - Vanguard does not
   - Vanguard charges **$20 annual fee** below certain asset levels (avoidable by electronic-only document delivery)

### Why the Free Ride?

**Why do Fidelity/Schwab offer free ride for other companies' ETFs?**

**They're not talking, but likely reasons:**

**Fidelity:** Wants to tempt you with actively managed funds

**Schwab:** More clear-cut answer
- Default sweep vehicle yields **0.40%** at time of writing
- **3.7% lower** than concurrent Vanguard Treasury Money Market Fund yield
- Financial author and advisor **Allan Roth** calculated: in 2019, **134% of Schwab's earnings** came from net interest (paying customers pitiful yield, loaning out balances at far higher rates)
- The 134% figure means rest of company operations lost money, including brokerage free ride

**Don't fall for games at either firm:**
- **Fidelity:** Stay away from actively managed funds
- Triple-check fund expenses before buying
- Be especially cognizant of difference between target date "Freedom" funds (high expenses) vs "Freedom Index" funds (competitive with Vanguard)
- **Schwab:** Keep cash balances at minimum with T-bill ladder purchase, short-term Treasury ETF, or separate money market funds (require separate transactions)
- **iShares 0-3 Month Treasury Bond ETF (SGOV):** Duration 0.1 years, approximates Treasury money market fund
- Main difference: net asset value (NAV) will vary (vs constant $1.00 of conventional money market fund)

### Payment for Order Flow (PFOF)

- Some brokerages pay for free trading with **payments for order flow**
- Mechanism: rebates from wholesale brokers executing trades (profit from bid/ask spread on stock or ETF)
- Currently: Schwab accepts PFOF; Fidelity and Vanguard do not
- **Vanguard's advantages:** Higher money market interest, superb ETF executions (plus); poor service, lack of online banking (minuses)
- Still slight nod to Vanguard for open-end funds because of company investment culture (nonprofit structure returns savings to funds' shareholders)
- Schwab, State Street, BlackRock: publicly traded companies, suffer from conflicts of interest between companies' shareholders and funds' shareholders
- Fidelity: owned by Johnson family; privately held companies' ethical behavior generally lies between mutualized and publicly traded firms

**Example:** Vanguard returns **100% of profits from share lending** to funds' shareholders; Fidelity, Schwab, BlackRock/iShares don't
- These profits tiny for large-cap funds but more important for small-cap funds
- Because of opaque compensation structure, even Vanguard not entirely above suspicion

**Competition will only intensify** — stay tuned, relative advantages/disadvantages can easily change

## The Portfolio Workhorse: Total Stock Market Funds

**All major investment companies offer total market index funds for US equities:**
- Fidelity, Vanguard, BlackRock, State Street, Schwab
- Each offers vehicles in open-end or ETF wrappers (often both)
- Listed in **Table 18.1**

**Table housekeeping notes:**
- All listed Vanguard funds are Admiral Class shares (in most cases carry fund minimums of $3,000; some can run as high as $50,000)
- Given enormous, ever-growing number of open-end funds and ETFs, tables cannot be comprehensive or up to date
- Example: Listed Dimensional's ETFs but omitted open-end funds (available only to those with affiliated advisors or some DC plan participants)
- Keep current on evolving fund scene with Morningstar fund research utility (described in **Chapter 15**)

### Open-End vs ETF: Trading Psychology Difference

**Biggest difference:** Trading psychology
- **Long-period returns:** matters little which wrapper chosen
- Choice depends on how you deal with psychology of:
  - **Open-end funds:** End-of-day pricing
  - **ETFs:** Continuous pricing throughout day (you decide when to pull trigger)
- Both situations can cause small amount of stress
- Personal preference matter

**Expense ratios:** Near-zero (Fidelity's case: zero)
- One of these funds sufficient on equity side for simpler asset allocations from **Chapter 7**

